title: For Sale:  Colt Diamondback .38 4 inch Barrel
postcontent:
Up for sale is a rare gem, a Colt Diamondback .38 special revolver. Blued finish and a 4 inch Barrel, no box or paperwork. The Colt snake series were hand crafted custom shop guns and are arguably the finest revolvers ever made. The fit, finish, buttery smooth trigger, and accuracy of these legendary revolvers is second to none. Colt has publically stated that they have no intention of ever reproducing the famous snake series because Colt no longer has the expertise and master pistolsmiths needed to make them.
     The Diamondback has a slighty smaller frame than the famous Python and is prized for having better ergonomics for shooters with smaller hands. Also ideal for women. I personally prefer these over the Python because I never saw much advantage in a .357 over a .38 unless you're using it for hunting. .357 typically means a larger bulky frame, more weight, issues with over penetration and a lot more recoil.

ATTENTION: For all you Colt collectors who like to bring a jeweler's loop to look at pistols. This revolver is a shooter, not a safe queen. If you're looking for an immaculate pristine unfired condition museum piece, this isn't the gun for you. That being said the firearm is in decent used condition, nice shiny good rifling in the barrel, not too much wear on the finish so it's still pretty, good lock up, and beautifully smooth trigger. The only flaws are the usual little nicks and blemishes you typically see when a pistol has been used and fired, nothing obvious. The biggest eyesore is a previous owner used a metallic silver paint to brighten up the front sight blade and they also put two little paint dots on the rear sight. This can probably be easily removed without damaging the original finish underneath, I just never bothered with it because the paint actually does a good job of making the sights more visible.

The price reflects the condition of the firearm and is quite reasonable compared to what they typically go for on auction sites or at gun shows. If it was brand new in the box, I'd be asking for a lot more, so don't waste my time with low ball offers. Not really interested in trades but if you have something rare and interesting you can always try your luck. (FYI a smith M&P or mass compliant ruger is neither rare nor interesting)

title: For Sale:  SMITH & WESSON ~ MODEL 27-2 3-1/2 Bbl... Shape, Cased...Mfd 1979, .357 MAGNUM
postcontent:
Here's a very nice Smith & Wesson Model 27-2 .357 Magnum. Built on the big N-frame, this revolver wears the desirable 3-1/2" pinned barrel with adjustable sights. The chamber mouths are counter-bored ("recessed") and the top strap and barrel rib are finely checkered in the tradition of the pre-war Registered Magnum. Overall condition is excellent with about 98% of the original bright blue finish remaining. There are a few minor handling marks and a light cylinder turn line, but no rust or any pitting. It has been fitted with a very nice set of earlier diamond checkered target stocks. The stocks show only light wear and are without cracks or chips. The mechanics are in excellent shape with good timing and rock-solid lock-up. The bore is likewise excellent. Internally, this revolver appears as new/test fired only. It comes with the original mahogany wood case which is in good condition except for some damage to the internal liner. The original owner also placed the box label on the back of the case (easily removed if desired). Also included are a 4" cleaning rod, brush, mop, screw driver, instruction sheet and miscellaneous factory paperwork. The serial number places her in about 1979-80 production. A very nice N-frame!
